Someone added a spinAngle parameter to this method and then decided that an angle of 0 was invalid.  This forces you to use 90 (as seen in guiTreeViewCtrl) in order to have a not very square 'square'.

A quick solution is to provide a path for a 0 spinAngle such as this:

```
if (spinAngle == 0.0f)
{
  for( S32 i = 0; i < 4; i++ )
     verts[i].point += offset;
}
else
{
  MatrixF rotMatrix( EulerF( 0.0, 0.0, spinAngle ) );

  for( S32 i = 0; i < 4; i++ )
  {
     rotMatrix.mulP( verts[i].point );
     verts[i].point += offset;
  }
}
```

I might also suggest giving spinAngle a default value of 0.0f.

found in Engine/source/math/mathUtils.cpp, these two methods are not implemented correctly. For randomPointInCircle, it looks like it is randomly picking from the square made by -radius to +radius and hoping that it's in the circle given.

I've included some quasi-C++ pseudocode (I'm quite new to C++) for randomPointInCircle  below, I'm not sure how the code would work for randomPointInSphere.

``` c++
Point2F randomPointInCircle( F32 radius )
{
   AssertFatal( radius > 0.0f, "MathUtils::randomPointInRadius - radius must be positive" );

   Point2F out;

   \\Randomly picks a point by randomly selecting a length of size maximum the given radius of the circle
   \\and then rotating it around the origin a random number of degrees.
   \\then you get the point on the circle from trig.
   float r = sgRandom.randF(0,radius);
   float theta = sgRandom.randF(0,2*pi);

   out.x = r * cos(theta);
   out.y = r * sin(theta);

   return out;
}
```

For  randomPointInSphere, the issue is roughly the same.

If you bind gamepad controls for UI input, they don't work until you've started a game at least once in a session.

Expected: Gamepad functionality is enabled when the application launches.

Steps to reproduce:
1. Bind a gamepad control to a new map for the main menu.
     new ActionMap(mainMap);
     mainMap.bind( gamepad, "btn_a", selectOption );
2. Push the mainMap ActionMap in the  mainMenuGui::onWake() function.
    mainMap.push();
3. Pop the mainMap ActionMap in the mainMenuGui::onSleep() function.
    mainMap.pop();
4. Create a function selectOption.
    function selectOption(%val)
    {
       if ( %val)
          echo("A Button Pressed");
    }
5. Launch T3D.
6. On the main menu press the A button.
7. Observe the log does not show the correct output.
8. Start a game in any mission.
9. Exit the mission back to the main menu.
10. Press the A button.
11. Observe "A Button Pressed" appears in the log.
